FUNCTION: strip_space

In [330]:
def strip_space(d):
    '''Strips white spaces from the dataframe columns of type Object'''
    df_obj = d.select_dtypes(['object'])
    #Selecting the Object type variables because numeric variables doesnt have white spaces
    d[df_obj.columns] = df_obj.apply(lambda x: x.str.strip())
    return d

FUNCTION: replace_unknowns

In [331]:
def replace_unknowns(d):
    '''Replaces ? with nulls'''
    d=strip_space(d)
    #Run strip_space first before 
    d.replace('?',np.NaN,inplace=True)
    return d

FUNCTION: mapp_education

In [332]:
def mapp_education(d):   
    '''Mapping Education to EducationNum based on a dictionary derived from grouping Education and EducationNum fields'''
    presence=d['EducationNum'].isna()
    for index in d.index:
        if presence[index]:
            key = d.loc[index, 'Education']
            d.loc[index, 'EducationNum'] = Education_dictionary[key]
    d['EducationNum'].replace(0,np.NaN,inplace=True) 
    #Education field not needed we will use EducationNum field instead
    d.drop(['Education'],axis=1,inplace=True)
    return d

Label Encoding Now

In [82]:
le = preprocessing.LabelEncoder()
def label_encode(d):
    for column_name in d.columns:
        if d[column_name].dtype == object:
            d[column_name] = le.fit_transform(d[column_name])
        else:
            pass
    return d

import scipy.stats as stats
from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency

The Null hypothesis is that there is NO association between both variables. The Alternate hypothesis says there is evidence to suggest there is an association between the two variables.

In [252]:

In [254]:
def _print_chisquare_result(col, alpha):
    result = ""
    if p<alpha:
        result="{0} is important feature for Prediction".format(col)
    else:
        result="{0} is not an important feature for prediction".format(col)
    print(result)
In [255]:
dfObserved=None
alpha=0.05
for col in df.drop('Income',axis=1).columns:
    X_ = df[col].astype(str)
    Y_ = df['Income'].astype(str)
    dfObserved = pd.crosstab(Y_,X_) 
    chi2, p, dof, expected = stats.chi2_contingency(dfObserved.values)
    dfExpected = pd.DataFrame(expected, columns=dfObserved.columns, index = dfObserved.index)
    _print_chisquare_result(col,alpha)

In [389]:
def plot_confusion_matrix(cm):
    '''A function to show labeled confusion matrix'''
    plt.figure(figsize=(5,4))
    ax= plt.subplot()
    sns.heatmap(cm,fmt='g', annot=True, ax = ax,cmap=plt.cm.Blues); 
    # labels, title and ticks
    ax.set_xlabel('Predicted labels');ax.set_ylabel('True labels'); 
    ax.set_title('Confusion Matrix'); 
    ax.xaxis.set_ticklabels(['<=50K','>50K']); ax.yaxis.set_ticklabels(['<=50K','>50K']);

Output and Conclusion¶

Since this is a slightly imbalanced dataset, I wont be using accuracy, precision, and auc as my metric and I will go with highest f1 score for class label 1 (>50K). Since there is a high cost associated with misclassifying an individual when they are earning <=50K and our model classifies them as someone who is earning >50K. Based on that metric XGB Classifier worked best for us. Since it had the lowest misclassification of individuals when they are earning <=50K and our model classifies them as someone who is earning >50K, i.e 1161.
